\begin_layout Subsection
Human-Robot Interaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proxemics in HRI may be influenced by a variety of factors, such as task
 and social relationship 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kim2014social"

\end_inset

, direction and body positioning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "torta2013design"

\end_inset

, relationship length 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "walters2011long"

\end_inset

, personal experience, personality, and gaze 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "takayama2009influences"

\end_inset

, and more 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kruse2013human,walters2009empirical"

\end_inset

.
 In a study by Kim and Mutlu, proxemic distance, or physical distance, is
 examined in conjunction with task distance (collaborative versus competitive)
 and power distance (supervisor versus subordinate) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kim2014social"

\end_inset

.
 In this card matching task, participants performed better with a greater
 physical distance (120 cm versus 46 cm) and reported a more positive experience
 with a subordinate robot when it kept a greater physical distance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kim2014social"

\end_inset

.
 While most of the human-human interaction (HHI) based hypotheses found
 support, some has no support and may be an indication that humans may interact
 differently with robots in certain contexts.
 However, the experimental design may not have used a complicated enough
 task, particularly for examining power distance and the benefits of a collabora
tive relationship may have been lost.
 For our purposes, the results of the study indicate that a subordinate
 robot, like Astrobee, should tend to maintain a farther distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other studies have examined the approach of a robot to a human or vice versa,
 and measured the minimum resulting distance where the participants felt
 comfortable.
 Torta et al.
