\begin_layout Section
Evaluation of Results 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed project aims to understand the effect of proxemic distance
 models (cost function and APF) on the path planning and execution of autonomous
, human-aware navigation by Astrobee.
 As the project is done in a simulation and leverages past research for
 empirical models of proxemics distance with no human feedback, the analysis
 will not include the subjective measures typically included in proxemics
 (comfort, naturalness, sociability, etc.) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kruse2013human"

\end_inset

.
 Instead, the analysis will focus on the results of path planning and execution
 to answer the following questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How long did it take for the robot to complete the task? What was the average
 velocity?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What was the distance travelled by the robot during the task?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What was the instantaneous distance between the robot and the human? How
 much time and distance did the robot spend within human-human interaction
 proxemics distance categories established by Hall 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hall1966hidden"

\end_inset

? What was the minimum distance?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Were there any collisions and if so, how many?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The questions listed above will be applied to each proxemic distance model,
 and the results compared to each other to ascertain if there is evidence
 to support use of one architecture over the other.
 The resulting discussion will also address tradeoffs between human acceptance
 and robot motion efficiency, and compare our results to previous studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, the objective function laid out in the COMPANION optimization function
 will provide a good basis for quantitative comparison between the methods.
 In addition, we will perform a qualitative comparison to evaluate gross
 differences in the sociability of the generated paths in different scenarios.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the literature review to date, a consistent and obvious avenue
 for future work was apparent: incorporation of physiological signals for
 real-time feedback of proxemics distance.
 Currently experimental setups with physical robots and humans rely on questionn
aires (e.g.
 Likert scales) after the human-robot encounter, and pose several limitations.
 Post-experimental questionnaires are dependent on accurate recollection,
 and in this context, cannot be used real-time.
 It may be possible in an experiment to have a human indicate discomfort
 by pressing a button, but this would not be desirable in an applied setting
 where robots should not increase any burden.
 Therefore, it would be desirable to translate physiological signals (measured
 in a way that is not invasive) to emotional states, primarily discomfort.
 Chandler briefly reviewed various options, where the galvanic skin response
 and facial expression reading appear the most promising 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chandler2012biometric"

\end_inset

.
 Research in affect recognition has sought to evaluate classifier accuracy
 across a variety of supervised machine learning algorithms and physiological
 signals
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kulic2007affective,rani2006empirical"

\end_inset

.
 As an alterantive to phsyiological signals, Best et.
 al describe the use of a machine learning algorithm to discern the likely
 social signal (e.g.
 angry) from social cues, such as head movement and gait 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "best2016clustering"

\end_inset

.
 Social cues may be interesting to investigate as another input source,
 but the classification accuracy was lower as several social cues appeared
 across social signals.
 Physiological signals appears better suited for the next step in this research
 to achieve the desired application.
 Incorporation of physiological signals will require collaboration across
 disciplines, like physiology and machine learning, and is expected to improve
 HRI.
\end_layout

